Republican strategy to resist Obama 's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by calling for a fight against election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that cases of election fraud in the United States are rarer than deaths from lightning strikes.
And Republican lawyers have counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is for sure: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions are partly discrediting the American democracy system.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That's why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that make it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 election, which brought 675 new seats to Republicans in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed restricting voting rights in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the voting period, eliminate the right to register the voter on the day of the ballot and strip citizens of the right to vote who have a conviction.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of a law passed in Indiana in 2008.
Republican authorities rushed to spread the practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they've initiated bills requiring voters to present photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal ID card like a health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, or 21 million people, who are of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by their state government.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
The cost of getting a required ID is often more than $100.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters 18 to 29 years old don't have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Students - voters who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates - are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their school in several states.
But those same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs who vote mostly Republican to use the ballot papers issued by those clubs.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
This is the first time such a requirement has been introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than 10 states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at restricting voting rights for Latin Americans.
Two-thirds of Latin American voters are believed to vote for the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 to abolish voter registration on voting day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those who wish to register.
That restriction has not gone unimpeded.
For example, during the 2004 election, a campaign to register voters helped to register some 10 million citizens.
At the same time, the measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the registration rate of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states passed laws aimed at reducing the voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of early voters were African-American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state's total.
The same thing happened with Latin Americans.
They represented only 11% of the electorate, but they represented 24% of the citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, who made up 76% of voters, early voters made up only 46%.
Of course, the Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to legislation restricting voter registration.
Several bills were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most ambiguous laws were suspended by the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This allowed for a partial reduction in negative consequences.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID.
However, the new rules that have come into effect will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics from Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that were passed, seeing them as clearly aimed at influencing the results of the 2012 election in key states.
The Brennan Center's 2011 report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions are partly discrediting the American democracy system.
