Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, reports that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused a stir - and not without reason.
This boson is thought to explain the mass of all the particles in the universe, not much nor little.
It's also the last particle that was predicted to exist in the Standard Model -- our best, or at least "least imperfect" description of the nature and behavior of matter -- but that hadn't been previously detected experimentally.
But physicists aren't quite sure what the Higgs boson is.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we're dealing with a really new particle and that it's very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, new data presented this week at a major physical convention in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data are not yet complete.
But let's say it's a Higgs boson, because the chances of getting it wrong are minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is, in this world, one absolutely inevitable law that says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way around that rule, don't even try too hard or you'll hurt yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it also turns out to have one law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same quantum state.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
On one corner, we find decent citizens called fermions who wisely obey Paulie's principle.
The other is the bosons, a loathsome gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least this principle, which means they can be at peace in the same place at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Particle Adventure Lab's (by the way, quite unusual) site, these bosons are in turn divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't talk about here, and "force particles", which are the primary forces of nature that are transmitted through and to which the Higgs boson is somehow related.
These bosons themselves, it should be emphasized, are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it's because of one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "courier" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it violates the electromagnetic field at that particular location, like a rock thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore one of the "force carriers" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, except that in order for that boson to appear, another field must be "intruded", the Higgs field.
But the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to trigger it, you have to reach very, very high energies, like a frozen pond whose surface can only be shaken by a very large rock.
That's why we need a huge particle accelerator like the one used in CERN -- the Large Hadron Collider, a ring 27 kilometers in diameter! -- to achieve such huge energies.
An analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with an electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, interact with each other, and some, like no, like a piece of paper, never stays on the fridge.
Likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like photons, by the way) don't.
So what can all this research bring, Mrs. Plamond asks?
In science, they are used to test the accuracy of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to sense the discrepancy between the results of observations and the predictions of the SM.
And some of them are eager to see that discrepancy, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door to "new physics" and close some of the Model's holes.
The latter, I must say, still has significant flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (ow!) or for dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe (ow-ow!).
But so far, there's been no such discrepancy at CERN.
The consequences
The benefits of this research for the average person's daily life are harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
Look, in the early '60s, pioneers of laser research at Bell Labs couldn't even imagine what revolution their work would bring.
They predicted their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the previous ones were pulsed) himself in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered more like a "laboratory gadget".
I mean, imagine...
And you can also find the app for the research toolkit.
For example, the same William Boyle, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although not its original purpose, is now the "eye" for all digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, doesn't mean that the Big Hadron Collider's work will necessarily change our lives, but it just shows, in fact, that anything can happen.
