Pay and sell without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of the current central bank-based money exchange, numbered transactions between recipients and fees for processing them.
And as is often the case with these technologies, there is a political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, which consists of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure BitTorrent-like exchange protocol that allows file sharing between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded from 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoin as a donation or payment.
The Bitcoin price, peaking at $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, dropped to $2 five months later before returning to about $10 today (currencies are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the global exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency published in October took an interest in this system.
He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro", and "like ordinary currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, such as "credits" used to promote video games, which are earned in the process of playing or which can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But the exchange is always controlled and processed by some central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously bookkeepers, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually happens between two email addresses, just like email.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The information set relating to this transaction is signed electronically using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file allow us to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger sent across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through solving a mathematical problem sent to the computers that solved it, like a central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
It's a phase of file hashing, which is converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers take a new transaction and add a number to it before they hash it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily verify it's correct.
The transaction thus proves to be inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If a user wanted to pay twice the same amount of money in less than ten minutes to cheat, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed because they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
