Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of European Space Agency ministers, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began its close cooperation with the ESA in 1994 and during the following years took an active part in a number of agency projects.
But Poland's journey to space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, but this was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who presented ideas from his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Cosmonautics" at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on December 6, 1933.
The ideas of the young engineer (1905), left the audience indifferent, after several years, Sturnfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and Andre Louis Hirsch prize for "Introduction to cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great proponent of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned cosmonaut and his contributions were appreciated, including the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in his honor.
In 1925, a railway train was built in Poland, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea and the details of the project remain unknown.
It's not even clear if the rocket was used to dislodge or to brake the carriage.
The information about this dress is known only from the press of that era.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The research was carried out by the Arms Techniques Section in cooperation with professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokjicki.
The surviving material shows that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937 the idea of a photoelectric fighter-rocket was introduced in the specialized press, which was proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, and the following year the work "Air-torpedo rocket and air-bomber rocket" by the author of the book, Lelieva-Kjivoblotsky, was published.
Both projects were designed for military missile engines.
Before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile technology projects.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, the work was terminated due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronavtics Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The Society was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal "Problemas", which published four volumes of articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
From the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (POA) tried to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn of the PWA became its member.
The following year, the first chairman of the IAA, Kazimeg Zarankievich (1902-1959) became the vice chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to perform scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, capable of reaching a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long, and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 two-stage RM-2 rockets were tested in the Bledovsk Desert.
This rocket was about 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kilograms.
The next version of the rocket was already capable of doing real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could travel 14.5 km, and its task was to observe high winds.
But in 1962, further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM type of rocket was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and a starting weight of 32,5 kg.
Three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and the Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a launch weight of 380 kg was capable of carrying a useful load of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Then versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning that Poland joined COSPAR (Committee on Space Studies) in 1960 and established the national COSPAR committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germanshevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
