Spikeniss, a small sleeping town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 people has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to public education and build seven imaginary bridges, depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of painted miniatures of iron concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the city fathers realized that they had only one way to beat the statistics: to build a library here!
Viny Maas of the Rotterdam architectural bureau MVRDV, a master of bold columnar diagrams and the author of witty, sometimes even cynical constructions, responded to the task with his usual calmness and appeared at the audition in 2003 with five books under his nose and a smile on his face.
And as the jury members looked around and shouldered, the bold Maas folded a pyramid in the size of his original gift and finished his speech in defense of his project with the words, "Dear Citizens!"
Here's my offer: the Book Mountain in Spikeniss, called the Bukenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain has grown to a value of 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, supermarket, post office and several adjacent residential houses and townhouses totaling 50 apartments.
In early November, the "Book Mountain" was awarded the second prize of the "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012" competition.
The project also participates in the 2012 Dutch national wooden buildings competition.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a strikingly ugly town hall whose white facades suggest a dairy factory, became richer for one modern architectural work.
But most importantly, the town of Spekennis has the first public building of cultural significance.
