"We wanted to work with secondary materials", explains Yop Trauborst, project manager for the community of Spekenniss, in line with the standards.
And one day, at an agricultural establishment in Friesland, we came across a suitable agricultural byproduct.
For many years, artificial fibrous materials of millimeter thickness have been used as a rootstock in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It's cheap and time-saving.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons, then they can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas -- the first of its kind -- was pressed into a four-centimeter-thick panel.
