Why? Why?
Stefan Saba: Germany does not support the Israeli actions in Gaza.
Now Germany needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I think she's not supporting the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, but not to be too critical of Israel.
During the 2011 uprising in Libya in March, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
NATO eventually made the offer.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, moving from the policy that the US, so to speak, was running, to the German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the lack of a coherent policy among Europeans.
So the Germans are again between the two fronts.
They're expected to play a more independent role, but they're not used to it.
I think they're just starting to see their roles, but they're on their way to a more normal foreign policy.
It's a foreign policy like France or Britain.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It's a willingness to take a stand in their national interests that is independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and connections to certain regions, like Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests differ greatly from those of other major states, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Persian Gulf.
So she needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in the Arab world.
Either way, it's got a role to play.
But I wouldn't take it too seriously, it's not a one-way communication.
But in any case, it plays a big part in the Germans' calculations.
Did Germany damage its relationship with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States there is a prevailing understanding of the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic a violation as the Libyan issue.
Germany may even gain some respect.
It's a sign that she should be taken seriously as an international player and that her interests should be taken seriously.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has been clear on the veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But given the local political situation, the government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that substantial differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you'll notice that Obama is not at all happy with Netanyahu's policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a single, uncontroversial European policy, but that is not the case now.
So they can't take a broader approach and instead have to act on their own vision.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
It's not easy for Germany, of course, at least because of its ties to Israel.
This has always been a hot topic.
But I think the Germans know they need to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not really take the lead?
Or is it still hard for Germany to take the lead?
Germany is not yet used to this, it is still always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still always difficult to play a significant role.
