"When I arrived at her house, it looked like her body had been washed before", recalls Mrs. Buendia.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and the body was already in the woods.
Mariana's mother recounted the story, and her daughter's portrait looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to a cross with only one word written on it: justice.
That's what they say this family was denied.
"State officials treated me like an old gossip girl, a disgruntled peace-breaker.
They want people to just take what they say for granted and shut up.
But it's wrong, it's not right, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around", she says.
By wrapping the presidential oath on Saturday, President Pena Nieto will take on a heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has vowed to make solving this problem a priority during his presidency.
"I hope he will be exactly the same president as the governor", says Olvera, a PRI congressman from Valle de Bravo.
But that's what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nescabad fear most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, the prosecution says.
Prosecutors are trying to disprove Bradley Manning's claims about poor conditions in custody.
During the hearing, much attention was paid to Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is calling for the case to be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions were harsh.
The U.S. Army is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, prosecutors tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, had missed the many opportunities he had to file a complaint about the mistreatment he said he had endured while in a military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fein stated that records of Manning's weekly visits by prison officials during his nine months in Quantico, Virginia, contain no complaints of ill-treatment.
A cross-examination of the defense's motion to dismiss Manning's case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and sufficient punishment in themselves was conducted the day after Manning stated that while in custody he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were later published online on WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has not confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday's hearing, Prosecutor Fein and Manning reviewed reports that were filled in after Manning was visited by officials during his time in Quantico prison, where he was held under strict confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, the prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he considered the prison administration's treatment of him to be "preferable" and the general conditions of his imprisonment to be "very professionally organized".
The reports examined contain no complaints of ill-treatment, although Manning was directly questioned about the conditions of his detention, Fein claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concern about these issues orally and that administration officials who had visited him discussed these issues with him and said they would address them, but did not record it in writing.
"They recorded 'no problems' (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring up the subject in the conversation", says Manning.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained of mistreatment in January 2011 during a commission hearing about his suicide plans, which he had written out months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to get his "trauma prevention" regime removed and his prison terms relaxed.
Military officials explained that a restricted detention regime - lower than the surveillance regime to prevent suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner and to protect the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know I was okay, that they were going to cancel the trauma prevention program... that my life would improve, in my view", Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at the Naval Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said that he had suicidal thoughts in Kuwait and that he had lost consciousness one day because of the heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult not to let you know how your destiny is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world has shrunk to the size of Camp Arifan, to the size of my prison", Manning said Thursday.
- I thought I was going to die in this cage".
While in Quantico, Manning said, he spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day - in total solitude.
Manning reports that he was only allowed to leave a mattress, a blanket, slippers, a few items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move, because sleeping or even just lying down during the daytime was prohibited by the rules.
Manning said that during sleep, he was constantly struck by light penetrating from outside the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around in bed at night, he said, they woke him up and forced him to turn around.
Manning's lawyer formally objected to the wrongful treatment of Manning in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about a statement he made during his testimony on Thursday that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked before guards and other prisoners at the morning checkpoint.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself in a blanket during the inspection.
In response to a judge's question on Friday, Manning said he learned from the guard's order that he should drop the blanket he could cover himself with, but admitted that no one had directed him to drop it.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked the night before because he tried to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reported telling the officer that he could use a rubber coat or a pair of scissors to injure himself, but he didn't.
That night, Manning testified, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from the camera.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to live through while in custody and significantly reduce his sentence if Manning is found guilty by a military court, which is due to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it planned to offer Manning a plea of guilty to lesser charges and to challenge the other charges as excessive.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico under strict rules governing the detention of detainees.
The charges against Manning include aiding an enemy, illegally facilitating the publication of data on the Internet, transmitting information relating to national defense, and stealing state property or documents.
If convicted on all charges, he could face life in prison.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of a Mexican-American.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of a lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of difficult times.
Ruben Navarrete believes that Mexican Americans are torn between two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down a corridor, approached a border control area, and froze.
The signs pointed to two rows: one for Mexicanos (Mexicanos), the other for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called Mexican all my life.
It's just a conditional name, like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and my friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later, I came to the complex design of "American of Mexican descent".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex designs.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
So I got my American passport and I got in line for the Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The agenda of the meetings of the presidents of these countries was on immigration, drugs and trafficking.
President Penia Nieto was eager to talk about the Mexican economy's rise, which would allow Mexicans to now, with the same success, stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to sign a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Penia Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and old-fashioned issue.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and, under the guise of rifle fire, forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and they see reminders of those events in everything.
So it's only fair for any US statesman to speak a word of criticism of Mexico, and the press and the elite of Mexican society are immediately complaining that Americans are invading the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montessori are full of war.
The most complex is Mexico's relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
You want to talk about the offense?
They're good enough.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities in this country, and those who don't.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for one reason only: at some point in their family history, someone -- father or grandfather -- didn't have the opportunity to establish themselves in Mexico and was forced to move north.
Most of them were Mexican people of a certain type - slumbers, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We're their descendants, and we remember that.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Our lives today are the fulfillment of the American dream, we've been to good schools and gotten good jobs, but let's not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and vague, but we know which country to consider our own.
The United States of America.
And we know that most of the Mexican elite and the ruling class don't like us.
We answer them the same way.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as unreal Mexicans.
We don't speak Spanish well enough, and our ties to Mexico aren't strong enough.
Our very existence is a failure for them.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We wouldn't be behind the silk curtain finding a life in the United States but losing our spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and moved to the U.S. legally as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain tensions between real Mexicans and Mexican Americans -- Mexicans have a clearer understanding of their national identity, and that's offensive to Mexican Americans.
She's a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my Mexican-American acquaintances don't feel like they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also like Bruce Springsteen.
Getting the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
We are Americans in Mexico.
And in the United States, we're called Mexicans.
Now, as I've learned during my trip, as if our relationship is not already confused enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to reestablish relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican Americans to be some kind of ambassador to Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a wonderful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course I did.
It's not gonna work.
Too many offences in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, the corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don't think this country is that beautiful.
I'm sorry, but you can handle this yourself, Amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still can't forgive the United States the way they did Mexico a century and a half ago, they'll have to accept the fact that some Americans of Mexican descent are still upset about how they treated their relatives in Mexico recently.
I did.
I think we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for a future peace
Is there a lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
There have been routine, meaningless debates about who started the first one; many buildings have been destroyed; over 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; rockets fired from the Gaza Strip have fallen for the first time in the conflict around Israel's capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the hopelessness of the Israeli and Palestinian conflict, the Middle East has changed.
There are many different ways to look at this, but the events of the Arab Spring have surrounded many established realities in a tumultuous storm, and the Palestinians and Israelis have not been able to stay out of the storm that has shaken the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will be even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons for hope to break through this deadly deadlock.
A war without winners
At first glance, the situation is not a cause for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire agreement signed on November 21 is upheld, this week's clashes have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, claim that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group's leaders have been killed and 1.7 million people trapped in one of the most densely populated and troubled parts of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity on the West Bank of the Jordan River - another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fath movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is running out.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and wealthy friends.
A reviving regional leader, Turkey, which was once Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, has backed Hamas; its example has been followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamically developing states in the Persian Gulf.
Hamas supporters are claiming to have an Islamic crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, ruled by Hezbollah's militant group, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar Assad, and then to Jordan, where the king's government threatens Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred at the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country, Egypt, where under President Mohamed Morsi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was ousted in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is an organization that is very similar to Hamas, and its leaders are more populist.
In future diplomatic settlements, Hamas could become a major player whose voice will not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the "hard line" in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli Iron Dome missile defense system justified the cost of its construction and successfully destroyed many of the Hamas missiles launched.
The citizens of Israel can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As for diplomacy, the United States has remained true to its unchanging position; many European countries have also blamed the beginning of the latest round of violence on Hamas.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which largely ignored the peace process.
Although about 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from Gaza since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, partly through a wall that enters the West Bank - much of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu's position, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - has joined forces with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What's the point of enslaving the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If we hand over all the power in the West Bank, won't they launch rockets from there toward Israel, like their fellow Gaza Stripers do?
Better to keep them behind the wall and stiffly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
The hardliners may win, but their calculations may be disproved by the Arab Spring.
While Islamists who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be domestic issues.
Israel's defense budget is bigger than all its Arab neighbors combined.
A war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on the ceasefire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel, in no small measure, should take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change moves in Arab countries, the Palestinian denial of self-determination is a slow-moving bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, just like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement are being paid for by growing international discontent.
Both sides need an outside impulse.
The only solution that remains is one that the sane representatives on both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper, are constantly calling for: the formation of two states and Israel's ceding of territories in exchange for security.
There is hope, not too impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the sides of the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long decided to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, and Turkey and Qatar, have a more favorable position than ever to convince Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state adopted since 1967 in the light of the sharing of territory and the shared use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the forthcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he still shows a reluctance to join the solution.
It's a catastrophic shortsighted position.
The United States is vital to stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible with a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, a law on the unified packaging of cigarettes has come into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and images of affected body parts are contrasted on dark green boxes, identical for all cigarette brands.
Australia's first ever law on the uniform packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color scheme of different brands with a gloomy olive box with scary images of sick body parts and images of children whose health is impaired by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the various paintings and inscriptions warning of the harm of smoking, the only difference between the packages that are mandatory from this Saturday is the names of the stamps that are printed in the same small font.
These are the toughest conditions in the world for packaging tobacco products.
The Australian federal government says that the aim of the measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving them of their harmful fashion status.
This decision was based on the results of studies that showed that 99 out of 100 people who did not start smoking before age 26 never became smokers.
"It is clear that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies try to convey by packaging", explains Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess in children.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest smoking rates in the world, so these changes will not have a significant impact on the profits of multinational corporations, but other countries are already considering such measures.
Tobacco industry officials strongly opposed the passage of the law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the black market share of cheap and affordable cigarettes.
"This bill will have serious consequences unlike those that were envisioned by its initiators", says Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit goods from China and Indonesia will supply far more of these goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, the new laws are promoting business growth.
Sandra Ha of the small family-owned company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that demand for portcagals and silicone cases that hide unpleasant pictures on packaging has grown rapidly (almost from scratch) since two months ago companies like British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a case in Australia's highest court, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 products to wholesale businesses and is expecting a new batch.
It's a good business for us.
Experts say that the popularity of social media is a potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures.
After Australia passed a series of laws that made illegal television advertising of cigarettes and their support of sporting events, and prohibited sellers from displaying cigarettes in public places, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from posting ads online, but it cannot restrict foreign sites.
"If you're a tobacco salesman and you're left with just this little loophole, the idea of promoting your product online is a very attractive one", explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes the rise in brand reviews written by supposedly ordinary users on social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
So the question is, is it really the work of a civilian who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spent his time and effort making a video, or is it the advertising company behind it?
British American Tobacco's Australian office claims that the industry is more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
Tobacco industry officials have even taken steps to sponsor Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: These countries are making claims to the World Trade Organization that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that all of these countries have very little trade relations with Australia.
The WTO is expected to reach a decision by mid-2013.
According to Taney Plibersek, the government has been discussing with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to make it mandatory to post pictures warning of the harm of smoking.
Now, this rule is in place in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey, and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening the laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are showing a lack of innovation.
I'm not interested in these pictures.
I'm just not paying attention.
"You just grab a cigarette and put it in your pocket", explains Victor El Haig, a buyer of cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on the pack.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me leave is my little daughter.
James Yu, head of the King of the Pack tobacco shop in downtown Sydney, claims that the same packaging has made it harder to arrange the goods on the shelves.
"I used to have an hour to unload a new batch, but now it takes four hours", he complains.
"The government should have taken and banned cigarettes altogether, and we would have said, 'What are we going to do, okay, we're going to close the store,'" he says, raising his hands.
It's not so bad to be bored in the world of electronic networks and constant connections.
On this Thanksgiving, I had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had a mechanical malfunction and was replaced by another plane we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and there's not much help in books, magazines, iPhones, or even duty-free shops.
However, in recent years, more and more children's development experts and scientists have expressed support for boredom.
They say that in certain situations, it's not so bad for us and our children to miss.
It forces the brain to focus on interesting related topics, which may help creativity.
And because in today's world, we're all constantly in front of a screen, the benefits of boredom are passed on.
Maybe we should strive for boredom.
I'm not.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to think, like many others, that boredom was an invention of the recent times when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Twy, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"In fact, boredom can boast a very ancient history", he says.
On the walls of Pompeii, Latin inscriptions about boredom have been found, dating back to the first century.
And the question remains, how do we understand boredom?
The problem, says John D. Eastwood, an adjunct professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, is that the understanding and view of boredom has often changed.
After studying research on the subject and asking a question to a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following conclusion: Boredom is when people "want but cannot do what will satisfy them".
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person does not do something he would like to do.
You don't want to do anything with apathy.
He says that the main cause of boredom is "a loss of attention and associated mood swings and a feeling that time is slowing down".
Boredom can be described as very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible link between these conditions, those who are bored see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances, and those who are depressed see the problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel bored when it's really just hard to focus.
In their study "Bedroomed Mind: Defining Boredom from the Point of View", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues cite an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading a journal.
Some participants also heard loud noises from a non-affiliated television program in the next room, others heard the same sounds at low volume, so they could barely be heard, and the third group listened only to a voice recording without an external sound track.
Those who listened to low-volume TVs reported being bored, more often than others - having difficulty concentrating, but they did not know the cause and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, distraction can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, an assistant professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "like looking through a supply chain in search of a marriage, distracting music can help us avoid boredom".
He goes on to say that when people start to roll around in a chair or draw a paperwork, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that actually doing so just helps keep them physically relaxed.
"The study showed that children who are not prohibited from flipping and rolling learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit quietly", says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we all get bored, like being delayed on a flight, listening to a monotonous speech, watching a movie that's not interesting.
However, different people have different degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, researchers developed a special "boredom scale" to measure these individual characteristics.
To determine a score on this scale, we use questions and statements like, "A lot of what I have to do is one-sided and monotonous" or "I'm too interested in too much, so there's no time for anything".
Using these questionnaires, researchers found that boys miss girls more often, says Stephen Wodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when there are a variety of external stimuli.
However, in general, teenagers often miss each other.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he used a pager to connect with nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
The results were as follows: 32% of teens reported being bored at school and doing their homework, and 23% reported being bored outside of school.
And only 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what this boredom data would be like 21 years from now.
However, he knows that "the peak of boredom occurs in adolescence", largely because children and adolescents are not fully allowed to decide what to do.
So back to my original question: Is boredom useful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, research shows, it can lead people to absurd and dangerous physical activity, risky gambling, or substance abuse in an effort to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have pondered the relationship between boredom and creativity, says Professor Wodanovich, who has devoted more than two decades to studying this problem.
"That's how our brains tell us to do something else; that's boredom", says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But that brain itself doesn't always know what the best thing to do is.
If you're bored and you put that energy into playing guitar or cooking, you'll do better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will not be bored, but he will not learn to deal with boredom on his own or in any other way to manage his time and his occupation", says Professor Fenske.
"And these self-regulatory skills are used in a variety of situations", he says.
Your child is not only learning to do things on his own, he is also learning to control himself in general.
I don't think boredom is something to be praised.
But it's not a bad thing to think of.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous flow of action and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
"We see this as a way to get bored more often, whereas boredom is an extremely unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful", he says.
People actually want to sort of cut off their constant worries and just relax.
"In today's world, we are accustomed to constantly over-stimulating our senses", he says, "and when silence strikes, we lose sight of what to do".
It's unclear how the new marijuana law will be enforced in Colorado.
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old soccer player and community college student in southeastern Colorado, is charged with a criminal offense that will soon be perfectly legal throughout the state: keeping a small portion of marijuana and a pipe he smoked in.
Mr. Orosco says that one September, he and his friends were in Lamar driving a car down the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by the police.
After a police officer discovered marijuana in the car, Ms. Orozco was summoned to court for possession of narcotics and a device for drug use - petty offences punishable by a fine of $100 each - and a court date has been set.
"We are treated like criminals", says Mr. Orosco.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that has persisted for weeks after Colorado voted to legalize recreational small amounts of marijuana, the resolution of hundreds of small-scale legal cases depends not so much on the law as on the venue.
Small-scale marijuana-related charges have already been filed in hundreds of cases here and in Washington State, which has taken similar action.
Police stations have already stopped charging people 21 years and older for keeping low doses, which will be legal once the law goes into effect in a couple of weeks.
However, in more conservative counties in Colorado, prosecutors have decided to consider existing marijuana-related cases and continue to hold the drug liable.
At the same time, some cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous West have voted to ban the opening of new, state-licensed marijuana stores.
"It's happening so fast, I don't even know what to expect", says Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, a city east of Denver.
The Washington State regulators are also puzzled to scratch their heads.
They must form rules to determine the licensing process for the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done by December 1, 2013.
They say that Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most other states in addressing marijuana use, first for medical purposes and now for recreation.
"Colorado is a more orderly market, so they will serve as a good example", explains Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Council on Alcohol Production and Sales in Washington State.
But now, Mr. Smith admits, there is nothing more anyone can do than make suggestions and hope that they work.
"We don't have a real precedent to look at", he says.
Washington State's bill, called I-502, will go into effect on December 6 and will leave the state in a state of uncertainty for a year when there is no state licensing system yet and marijuana possession is already legal.
And there are still some very difficult technical issues that need to be addressed in this period, like how to balance the state's "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a 1,000-foot ban on commercial use from schools, parks, playgrounds, and kindergartens.
"It will be especially difficult to locate licensed marijuana businesses in the city, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs", explains Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the newly formed Marijuana Legalization Center research group.
