The toughest profession in the world: Kawah-Ijen miners
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by smuggling 70 kilograms of sulfur up the volcano's summit along steep rocky paths
Some people think their jobs are hell, and some people literally work in hell.
Among them was Antonio Vijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living from the Kawah-Ijen volcano, located east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Antho descends to the bottom of the crater, where sulfuric gas rising from the Earth's depths freezes when it comes into contact with the air.
He puts up huge pieces of sulfur, which can weigh up to 70 kg, in two bamboo baskets, and he puts them on his shoulders and carries them up a rugged rocky road.
The volcano, which is 2,386 feet (2,386 m) high, is only 250 feet (250 m) high, but exhausted loaders take more than 40 minutes to climb with a turtle-like step, struggling to maintain balance and carefully stepping on the road so as not to fall or fall from the edge.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to a tourist from France who broke off the Cavache-Igen rocks a few years ago.
Miners from Kawah-Ijeen earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
Once they're up there, they're paving a path between tourists who photograph them as if they were a circus monkey and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, they're walking three kilometers to the weights that the mining company has placed a little higher, at 1,850 meters.
The company, which has been operating the volcano since 1960, and, better yet, its employees, is paid 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for each kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocents) to petrochemical companies, since it is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"Because it is normal to carry 70 kilograms, we make about 46,000 rupees (US$36,000) for each walk", explains Antonio, who normally moves three times a day.
He spends three hours on each and feels broken at the end, but they allow him to save 138,000 rupees by the end of the day.
Although it may seem a pity for such a dishuman effort, it's three times what he would earn in the field.
"The daily wage for miners is very high by local standards, where coffee collection costs 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros)", explains a freighter who used to work as a stonemason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees a day and the plot was not so heavy, but he returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a reason that is as devastating as the grimness of Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali, where there are only Hindus, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, he has difficulty breathing, constant coughing, and he's tearing his eyes out of toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Antô spent three years risking himself in Kavach-Ijén, whose gray matter had already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he has difficulty breathing, he coughs constantly, and he's tearing his eyes out because of the toxic gases that the volcano releases.
