UNASUR summit ends without the publication of the Lim Declaration
The VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNESCO) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lime Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the 6th UNASUR meeting of Heads of State and Government, but sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the homepage that it would be forwarded after closure, but then confirmed that at some point it would be published on the Peruvian government website.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the content was presented by Peruvian President Olyanto Umal during brief press releases.
Journalists' access to information about the Summit was limited at all times.
During the day, a video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room without sound, with the message "closed session, sound prohibited".
A little information circulated among reporters was given by press secretaries of some UNASUR governments who were present at the meeting, but not Peruvian.
The only document circulated during the day was a list of participating presidents, which caused the discontent of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
The Peruvian presidential administration later sent a media email with the summit's "final declaration", but it's about Umalla's statement, not the official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and at that time, despite press pressing demands, the so-called Lime Declaration, which had been previously announced, was not published.
The official website of the ASPA can be checked to see if the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities tried to ensure that all journalists were provided with a broadcast system, but they restricted access to information to the maximum extent possible.
The summit also ended with Chile and Peru jointly deciding to accept the ruling of the Hague Court, which settles the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Olianto Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Piñera, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which begins hearing the statements of both sides in The Hague on Monday, as part of the indictment that Lima has brought against Santiago.
"We will comply with and enforce a decision that will clarify the differences we are currently bringing to this international court", Umala said, alongside his Chilean colleague.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, pacts and international tribunals", Pinera added, welcoming Umal with a wave of arms against the flags of the two countries.
Both presidents' confirmation of their compliance with the International Court of Justice came just after Colombia this week protested the Bogotá Pact, which recognized its compliance with the international court's rulings following a decision on its maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it deemed wrong.
The summit was held in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Christina Kirshner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR was suspended since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The president-elect, Olianto Umala, was responsible for opening the talks in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon Lime time.
The head of state read the final document, which reported that 16 agreements were adopted and 31 projects were approved among South American countries, the amount of the proposed investments amounted to 17 billion dollars.
Among the agreements he mentioned, UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the residence agreements".
He said action was being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and organized transnational crime, action to increase access to medicines, affordable Internet access in all parts of South America, and to take the risks of natural disasters into account in a collective and effective manner".
As Europe is in crisis, "the economic union (Latin America) should not be a triumphal foundation, but should serve to expand our production base and foresee a better future for our cities", Umala added.
"We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve connectivity across South America, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and creating new economic schemes", the Peruvian president said in a statement.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five are Peruvian and are limited to cross-axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at greater connectivity with Ecuador, but he did not provide further details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve its re-joining of the Union of South American Nations", from which it is now excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, to be united and to have good relations with its neighbors was another topic underlined at the summit.
In this regard, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before he would begin his regional meeting that he hopes to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to conduct a respectful negotiation on a maritime dispute as a result of the ruling of the international court challenged by Bogotá.
"Tomorrow (Saturday), I may meet with President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We will review all these paths, they are not mutually exclusive, including the Nicaragua pact will require discussions with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will deal with this as civilized and respectfully as possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico City on Saturday, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto.
Also during the summit, the bloc's defence ministers met in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and unanimity on the issue of protecting the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the latter is suspended.
Peru has a provisional presidency in the regional bloc.
