AIDS deaths today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 when he was told his AIDS test was positive.
"I felt like I was deaf", he recalls that difficult, despite the doctor's tact, moment.
The young man hid it from his family.
Deciding to deal with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn as much as possible about it, and his efforts were worth it - he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" HIV patients at the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he entered in 1994, overcoming many obstacles.
He's been living with the human immunodeficiency virus for 22 years, and it would have been hard to believe in the early '90s -- there were too few treatments then, too few people knew about the disease, too many people were biased.
So even the director of the clinic at the Mexican Institute of Social Protection refused to say goodbye to him "because he had a cut".
In other words, having AIDS was a sentence back then.
Now it's possible to survive the syndrome and do it without deteriorating quality of life.
Yet, many people still come to the hospital unaware of their illness when the virus has already damaged their immune system and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the world's first reported cases of AIDS, at least, "the greatest achievement so far is that the survival of a patient who begins treatment on time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same", said HCG HIV chief Jaime Andrade Vilyanueva, citing a prestigious scientific publication in April.
Infectious disease expert and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Vilyanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a sentence, but that the length and quality of life depends on the degree of immune system impairment that patients have at the time of diagnosis, with the best life expectancy in those who don't use drugs: up to 30 years with 200 CD4s, and up to 50 years when 500 CD4s are reported.
Simply put, the above means that a person diagnosed HIV positive at age 25, according to these terms, "with control, can live without problems until age 75", he explained.
To assess this progress, we need to remember that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
While mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has declined from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNICEF's annual report), and it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths have been recorded as of May this year; however, it is claimed that there is widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
- Personally, I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I imagine it is, that's how things are in our hospital.
At least for the last 12 years, we haven't had a shortage of medication, and the problem is that patients arrive very late because they don't know their infection status, which is, they're in the late stages of the disease.
He cited the overwhelming data: "Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some sort of opportunistic infection; what we need to do to make a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose at an earlier stage, and therefore we need to provide mass-detection samples to all people who ask for it".
The proposal is a joint venture between experts and officials at the State AIDS Council in Jalisco (COESIDA), as well as patients like Fabrizio, who went to a private laboratory for testing, motivated by the fact that his friend had done it and, despite his young age, had already been diagnosed with AIDS and even suffered from Kaposhi sarcoma, a cancer tumor that is one of the most common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
