"I'd rather get laid three times a week if I died anyway", they say.
I'm having positive changes, eating well, exercising, taking medication.
To date, all his parents know is that he has cancer.
I'm living a normal life like any other.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, taking care of myself and the other person", said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO to promote his statement to those who are now experiencing fear in the context of World AIDS Day.
Let them check for a risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, so better, and if they've already been diagnosed, let them know that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
This message summarizes the theme of the fight against AIDS this year.
Condoms on the shelf
There is a huge gap between health programs and the average citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has been working on the HIV problem.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "the spread of condoms has actually increased, we used to get one or two, now we get a hundred packs, which is very good, but it turns out that there are those who still don't have access to condoms", he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
